Whether framesaver is worthwhile is controversial. A lot of today's
generation of steel-minded cyclists who learned everything from the
internet are very sold on it without much feel at all for how
necessary it actually is.

Unless ridden in very salty conditions, like heavily salted roads,
bikes with typical butted tubes don't tend to ever have any functional
problems with internal rust. With a .8/.5/.8 tt, LHT's have one tube
that's a bit thinner than the much more common .6mm tubes that really
set the context, but it can still basically be considered a non issue
unless you're going to ride salty slushy stuff.

The downside of Framesaver is that it's nasty, smelly, very toxic shit
that you'll be carrying around forever, and it does cost money.

It's also important to understand that if you want to care about
internal rust, the absolute first and foremost thing to do is drill a
drainage hole underneath your BB shell. This allows a route of escape
other than gradual evaporation for water that does get inside your
frame, which makes a HUGE difference in terms of preventing rust. It's
insane and wrong that steel frames don't come like this. It's also
pretty silly that this isn't pointed out by all the various online
sources touting Framesaver.

Also, you can just use lube to coat the inside of your frame every
once in a while. You can do this by blasting a spray lube in or using
a liquid lube and then rotating the frame around to spread it. You'll
have to do it periodically and it won't be as effective as the
extremely tenacious Framesaver, but it does seriously help prevent
rust, which again is generally a non-issue to begin with.
