That does suck, but in the case of the chainstays, I wonder if it'd
actually ever be an issue in practice. I suppose it's a quesiton of
how much water the vent holes can actually let in even in extreme use,
since that's really the only way water is going to get into the
chainstays. However, the chainstays are a very typical .9mm at the
thick ends, like millions of other chromo TIG bikes built the same
way, and this doesn't seem to come up in practice on any of those
bikes, so it doesn't seem like much to worry about.

The only entry point that would get water into the downtube seems like
it would be the headtube opening, and it's hard to imagine enough
water coming in through there to actually collect next to the BB.

I think that if you're going to worry about this anywhere on the bike
other than the BB, it's water collecting in the top tube that's most
likely to cause problems. Water from the seattube opening can get in
there, it's got nowhere to go, and it's kinda far away from any kind
of vent for whatever that's worth  Once a friend of mine had the fork
out of his lugged Panasonic, being used as a daily PNW year-round
commute bike for a couple years, and I spotted a rather distressing
pool of rusty water there at the HT joint, a perfectly nasty place for
it no less.

