As an aside, my daughter kept her mountain bike outside for the better
part of a year and didn't have fenders or fender mount bolts installed
etc. quite a bit of water got inside through the bridge at the bottom
bracket where a fender bolt goes through. I literally lifted the front
end of her bike up and orange water poured out through the rear stay,
vent holes.
I will be taking her bike apart this winter and will inspect the
insides of her tubing with dental mirrors and perhaps a bore scope to
see how rusty or pitted the steel is.  After that, I will treat the
rust with a rust converter and then some Framesaver.
My old Centurion had numerous rust spots on the outside of the tubes
before powdercoating but the insides were really pretty clean and that
was on a 27 year old frame that had obviously been rode hard and put
away wet a few times. I think steel gets a bad reputation regarding
rust and advertisers play up the rust issue to keep people buying
aluminum. Of course aluminum corrodes, just like steel rusts, its just
that we don't talk about it.
I'm going to keep an eye on my new LHT frame and take all the
preventative steps to keep it unaffected by rust but I am not going to
let myself worry excessively about the whole issue. I figure I have
about 25 good years of cycling left so any frame I buy should last me
that long as I'm still riding two 20+ year old bikes now.

