On Aug 13, 7:57 pm, Chuck &lt;ChuckW ... @gmail.com&gt; wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Vent holes are only important during the framebuilding process.  Many
&gt; top framebuilders braze them up when the frame is complete, but you
&gt; can't expect that detail on a production tig-welded frame.  Plug 'em
&gt; with RTV or beeswax if you like.
">

As I understand it -and I'm still learning all this although I've read
a lot- there's no consensus about this on tubes that won't be
completely sealed. Many builders, doing lugged frames, seal the vent
holes on seatstays and fork blades. This completely seals those tubes,
preventing any oxidation beyond the negligible, probably invisible
amount caused by the oxygen trapped within.

Many builders have the opinion that any tube open at one end, such as
a chainstay is open to the BB on any typical brazed or tig'd frame,
should be open at both ends to allow moisture to escape. And others do
plug the chainstay vent holes, although I think that most handbuilt
brazed bikes don't ever have vent holes in the chainstays, not sure
why.

Again, I'm not an expert, but I do ride in the rain all the time, and
a bike full of vent holes has done me very well.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Drilling a &quot;drain hole&quot; in the bb shell - close to the ground and in
&gt; an area susceptible to spray from the front wheel - also seems like a
&gt; bad idea to me.  As Jobst Brandt once said &quot;Don't put any
&gt; gratuitous leaks in the frame.  Just keep it dry on the inside.&quot;  But
&gt; drill 'em if you like.
">

Water entering from the seat tube opening and causing rust in the BB
shell is a real issue on bikes that get ridden in wet conditions,
period. A drain hole helps mitigate this and is not going to let much
in at all, and is certainly something that good framebuilders include
( http://richardsachs.com/nuovorichiegallery/pages/NR-28.html ). Just
recently a friend of mine took out his BB on an LHT with no drain hole
that had been used for a couple years of constant Northwest commuting.
Totally rusty, and he's a mechanic and certainly greased it thoroughly
during installation.
