On my recent single speed project I had an old cup and cone bottom
bracket installed and after a 30 minute ride in pouring rain with no
fenders ( the kind where you can't see through your glasses) I noticed
a week later that the crank felt gritty. I took it apart and rusty
goop came out and the bearings were ruined. I replaced the bottom
bracket with a sealed unit and took out the rivet for the cable guides
effectively removing the cable guide as well. This created a drain
hole but my intention is to tap it and thread a bolt in it so I can
remove it to let any moisture drain. I suspect I won't have any since
I installed fenders and in the process plugged the fender bridge
behind the bottom bracket. Adding fenders also keeps water from
entering the headset and steer tube . The only place water can  get in
is the brazing vent holes. These don't usually allow water in if
fenders are used and the addition of beeswax (non permanent and
removable) should keep water out. The only problem is condensation
forming on the insides.........if you coat the innards with a
protectant and allow the inside to vent, it shouldn't be a large
problem, assuming there is no large amount of standing water
collecting and any that is inside can drain out a threaded drain hole
on the bottom bracket.
Keep in mind that most cyclists don't ride often in pouring rain. The
few that do are generally fairly savvy and end up with sealed bearings
and take steps to preserve their frame set.

