A couple of days ago a friend brought over his 80's Bianchi Limited
because his crank felt a little loose.  I pulled the bottom bracket
out and found small remnants of bearing holders, blackened ball
bearings that looked like old cannon balls, and piles of black dust
and rust.  It did not have a bottom bracket drain hole.  I have always
made sure that my frames have a drain hole.  As the Campy Bottom
Bracket instructions say, &quot;Make sure that there is a hole for water
drainage underneath the bottom bracket cage.  If there is no such
hole, do not simply create one.  Campagnolo s.r.l. recommends
contacting the frame manufacturer for further information and
clarification in this regard.&quot;  A few years ago after an especially
wet &quot;Assault on Mount Mitchell&quot; ride my LBS mechanic remarked that if
the riders didn't  disassemble and clean their bikes that he would
have lots of business with bottom brackets and wheels.
Happy Trucking!
Doug
